Analysis of League of Legends Games

Matthew Huang, Isaac Chen, Ingrette Wang

Released in October 2009, League of Legends has solidified itself as one of the most popular played video games for the past decade. At its core, League of Legends is a 5v5 MOBA (multiplayer online battle arena) game where two teams of players face off against one another, and race to see who can destroy the other teams base first. Although the game has evolved over its lifespan, the core gameplay of teams trying to create an advantage over the team has stayed consistent. Being a complex game with many factors influencing a games state and outcome, are there any specific factors that can predict the outcome of a game? These are some questions that we aim to answer in this tutorial.

What features make up a game of League of Legends?

The game takes place on a map with a main base (nexus), with three main lanes expanding out from the main base. Each lane contains an inhibitor, and three towers that protect enemies from entering the main base. The main objective of the game is to destroy the enemies main base by marching down one(or multiple) lanes, destroying towers and inhibitors along the way. Throughout the game, players from both teams are able to unlock and upgrade their champions abilities as they level up, which can be achieved through a couple of different ways. Players can level up by defeating enemy champions in combat, granting them experience, as well as gold, which can be used to buy items in an item shop that increases a players stats (attack damage, magic damage, movement speed, health, to name a few), which creates an advantage for that player. Another way that players can level up is through killing lane minions, which are NPCs (non-playable characters) that spawn every 30 seconds and grant gold and experience upon death.

More in-depth information about the game can be found here
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/League_of_Legends

In this tutorial, we will be analyzing how multiple factors such as gold difference, team color, and more features from around 10,000 Diamond ranked games, can predict a games outcome. By analyzing this data, we hope to better explore the different facets that contribute toward game results, and gain insights into strategies and patterns that lead to success in the competitive scene.

Data Curration

Our data was obtained through the Riot Games API, and was obtained through an uploader who classified the data as public domain. The format of the original data is contained in a csv file that contains 9,879 entries.
Because the raw data is already in numerical format so there is no need to convert our data to integers. However, we will be deleting some uncessary columns such as (blueFirstBlood, redFirstBlood, gameId, blueEliteMonsters, and redEliteMonsters) Based off our own experiences that we have from playing the game, these data values don't provide much value when it comes to analysis of game outcomes. The advantage earned from getting first blood is only 150 gold, which is pretty negligible in the grand scheme of the game. The number of elite monsters killed is also minor, as only one elite monster spawns within the first ten minutes of the game, and the buff it provides isn't enough to determine a game's outcome.

Now that our data is more cleaned up, we can use visualization to better see our data and how it relates to each other. To do this, we want to see whether any of these columns correlate with one another.

As League of Legends is broadly a resource gathering game (of the in-game currency, gold), gaining more gold generally leads to resource advantages that could allow the team with more gold to win the game. Total minions killed, kill count, CS per minute, objectives killed, assists, and first kill counts also influence the gold per minute, as killing minions, champions, and objectives all grant the player gold in the game. Total minions killed and objectives killed also influences CS (creep score) per minute, as minions and objectives killed contribute to a players overall creep score.

This means that there should be features that correlate with one another!

Below, we are running a function to see if there is any correlation between each of the columns. This test calculates the pairwise correlation coefficients between all numerical columns in our dataset/dataframe.

Looking at our heatmap, we will ignore the features that have a correlation of 1.00 because those features/variables are either being tested against itself, or the feature they are being tested against is directly correlated with it, meaning they are colinear(e.g. blueGoldPerMin vs blueTotalGold). To clean up our data more, lets remove the columns from the dataframe that have no correlation to blueWins.

    if (correlations[col]>0.15 or correlations[col]<-0.15):
        column.append(col)

# train/test split the dataset before normalizing/scaling
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = df_updated
y = df['blueWins']
seed = 42
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=seed)

# scale the features
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train)
X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

Decision Tree Classifier

In [81]:
# fitting the model
from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

decision = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier()

# search the best params
map = {'min_samples_split': [5, 10, 20, 50, 100]},

#grid search w/ cross validation (training model)
clf_tree = GridSearchCV(decision, map, cv=5)
clf_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

pred_tree = clf_tree.predict(X_test)


# get the accuracy score
dt_acc = accuracy_score(pred_tree, y_test)
print(dt_acc)
print(classification_report(pred_tree, y_test))

Insights and Conclusions

Based off our correlations and our ML analysis, factors to consider in a game include kills, gold, and experience. These features play more of a role when it comes to determining the outcome of a game. Because there is so much variation in a game of League of Legends, there is no one formula fits all where if you just focus on getting "x" amount of kills, or "x" amount of gold/experience difference, then you automatically win the game. Because games are played by actual people, players can make user errors, which can invalid the results of a game. For example, even though one team may have on average a higher amount of kills at ten minutes into the game, they could still lose the game due to other factors that happen after the first ten minutes. Additionally, becuse our data was uploaded four years ago, things may have changed, at least in relation to the professional League of Legends scene. Regardless, we hope that further research can be done on exploring game data as League of Legends continues to evolve.
